Calling AssetManager.unload() doesn't seem to remove Sounds from memory on iOS (iPad Air, iOS 7.1.1). As far as I can tell, this is working fine on both Desktop and Android. Calling Sound.dispose() on the sound directly seems to be fine. The leak is visible in Instruments, use a large file (e.g. "8.12.mp3" in gdx-tests) to make this as obvious as possible.

Apologies if I'm just misunderstanding the AssetManager.

Demo code: 

``` java
package com.mygdx.game;

import com.badlogic.gdx.ApplicationAdapter;
import com.badlogic.gdx.assets.AssetManager;
import com.badlogic.gdx.audio.Sound;


public class MyGdxTests extends ApplicationAdapter {
    public AssetManager manager = new AssetManager();
    int counter = 1;

    @Override
    public void create () {
    }

    @Override
    public void render () {
        if (counter == 1) {
            // Load up the sound
            manager.load("8.12.mp3",Sound.class);
            manager.finishLoading();
            System.out.println("loaded");
        }

        if (counter == 100) {
            // Check it's there 
            for (String s : manager.getAssetNames()) {
                System.out.println("before: " + s);
            }
            // Unload the sound
            manager.unload("8.12.mp3");

            // Check it's gone 
            for (String s : manager.getAssetNames()) {
                System.out.println("after: " + s); // Should never be seen (and isn't)
            }
            counter = 0;
            System.out.println("unloaded");
        }
        counter ++;
    }
}
```

